about what the results were?

00:05:03.747 --> 00:05:05.330
BOB BLENDON: So we'll
do this quickly,

00:05:05.330 --> 00:05:10.080
but the biggest finding is,
for 50 years in this country,

00:05:10.080 --> 00:05:14.480
we've been debating how to
help people who aren't insured.

00:05:14.480 --> 00:05:17.420
And the assumption is,
once you get them the card,

00:05:17.420 --> 00:05:19.790
they are protected for
the rest of their lives.

00:05:19.790 --> 00:05:21.830
And we're going to
take you in a world

00:05:21.830 --> 00:05:23.850
where serious little
people with insurance,

00:05:23.850 --> 00:05:26.780
including Medicare, are
facing staggering bills.

00:05:26.780 --> 00:05:28.640
It has nothing to do
with the dialogue we've

00:05:28.640 --> 00:05:30.050
been having for 50 years.

00:05:30.050 --> 00:05:32.000
You cross the Rubicon.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:33.930
Now, you're safe.

00:05:33.930 --> 00:05:35.780
So let's just do
this very quickly.

00:05:35.780 --> 00:05:38.960
First it buried in
every story about--

00:05:38.960 --> 00:05:43.480
first slide-- health
care in America

00:05:43.480 --> 00:05:45.800
is one in six people
who are extraordinarily

00:05:45.800 --> 00:05:47.760
ill over a three-year period.

00:05:47.760 --> 00:05:50.990
And so the people in
our sample, 100% of them

00:05:50.990 --> 00:05:52.760
were hospitalized
at least twice,

00:05:52.760 --> 00:05:56.000
said they had a serious illness.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:58.250
A quarter of them were
hospitalized five times

00:05:58.250 --> 00:06:00.080
in three years.

00:06:00.080 --> 00:06:02.850
They were mostly seeing
five doctors or more.

00:06:02.850 --> 00:06:05.800
So you talk about
information coordination.

00:06:05.800 --> 00:06:08.450
They are taking five or
more prescription drugs.

00:06:08.450 --> 00:06:12.590
And just to show, as we'll show
in a minute, insured America,

00:06:12.590 --> 00:06:18.350
one in 10 had $50,000 a year of
prescription medication bills.

00:06:18.350 --> 00:06:21.497
And these are people
who, in fact, say

00:06:21.497 --> 00:06:24.080
they're seriously ill, and they
have one of the major killers.

00:06:24.080 --> 00:06:27.020
So these are not
routine patients at all.

00:06:27.020 --> 00:06:30.500
Let's just take a
look at what happens.

00:06:30.500 --> 00:06:31.770
Next slide.

00:06:31.770 --> 00:06:35.960
So the gray bars are all 91%
of people-- good news-- had

00:06:35.960 --> 00:06:37.170
a health insurance policy.

00:06:37.170 --> 00:06:40.200
Wow, I can feel good about that.

00:06:40.200 --> 00:06:41.460
So here it is.

00:06:41.460 --> 00:06:43.230
I have a health
insurance policy.

00:06:43.230 --> 00:06:46.490
53% of people with a
health insurance policy

00:06:46.490 --> 00:06:47.930
had serious medical bills.

00:06:47.930 --> 00:06:49.910
They had problems paying it.

00:06:49.910 --> 00:06:52.130
And so a third were hospital.

00:06:52.130 --> 00:06:53.270
But I'm insured.

00:06:53.270 --> 00:06:56.220
Third, prescription
drugs, emergency rooms.

00:06:56.220 --> 00:06:58.370
These are not stories
about the uninsured.

00:06:58.370 --> 00:07:01.260
These are stories of people
who have an insurance card.

00:07:01.260 --> 00:07:03.950
All through our poll,
each section we ask you,

00:07:03.950 --> 00:07:05.430
what worries you most?

00:07:05.430 --> 00:07:07.444
Mostly, I don't know
how I can pay for this.

00:07:07.444 --> 00:07:09.860
Suddenly, they're being told
that this policy that they're

00:07:09.860 --> 00:07:12.930
lying in a bed with is
not going to do that.

00:07:12.930 --> 00:07:14.790
Next slide, please.

00:07:14.790 --> 00:07:17.270
So take quickly.

00:07:17.270 --> 00:07:21.230
So if you just look at the
gray bars, I have insurance.

00:07:21.230 --> 00:07:23.300
My family feels reassured.

00:07:23.300 --> 00:07:28.850
36% of the insured people
used up all their savings

00:07:28.850 --> 00:07:30.380
as a result of having this.

00:07:30.380 --> 00:07:32.170
They had insurance.

00:07:32.170 --> 00:07:38.900
21% couldn't pay for basic
necessities, having insurance,

00:07:38.900 --> 00:07:40.890
and lost the job.

00:07:40.890 --> 00:07:43.850
And we'll get back to this
in a minute, most people who

00:07:43.850 --> 00:07:46.850
work in America have
short-term sick benefits.

00:07:46.850 --> 00:07:47.500
Guess what?

00:07:47.500 --> 00:07:50.060
If I'm not sick over
these periods of time,

00:07:50.060 --> 00:07:51.830
my benefits run out.

00:07:51.830 --> 00:07:54.530
And my job sends
me a loving note

00:07:54.530 --> 00:07:58.650
about you may not be able
to continue for this.

00:07:58.650 --> 00:07:59.690
So we have that.

00:07:59.690 --> 00:08:02.430
And the last slide,
very quickly.

00:08:02.430 --> 00:08:05.390
So all of us have
stories that may

00:08:05.390 --> 00:08:08.450
have played that role, where a
friend or family member, when

00:08:08.450 --> 00:08:12.140
you go home from the hospital,
takes care of you for a while.

00:08:12.140 --> 00:08:14.930
But these are people
who have long a whiles.

00:08:14.930 --> 00:08:17.390
So this is the
financial experience

00:08:17.390 --> 00:08:19.280
of the person who
cared for you at home.

00:08:19.280 --> 00:08:20.570
Not you, them.

00:08:20.570 --> 00:08:23.360
So one in four of
those people had

00:08:23.360 --> 00:08:25.910
significant financial
problems because they

00:08:25.910 --> 00:08:29.630
had to cut back on the rest of
their lives, and 21% of them

00:08:29.630 --> 00:08:32.270
just said I had to care
for someone at home,

00:08:32.270 --> 00:08:35.100
I have a lower income
as a result of that.

00:08:35.100 --> 00:08:37.429
So just the two
takeaways from here.

00:08:37.429 --> 00:08:40.580
Now that we're moving away
from the uninsured debate,

00:08:40.580 --> 00:08:43.760
there's a serious problem if
you're seriously ill about

00:08:43.760 --> 00:08:45.770
whether or not your
insurance will cover you.

00:08:45.770 --> 00:08:48.710
Secondly, sick days,
which at Harvard

00:08:48.710 --> 00:08:51.110
may be terrific for as
long as you want to be out,

00:08:51.110 --> 00:08:53.580
are not that good
for other people.

00:08:53.580 --> 00:08:56.210
And if you have a
long-term illness,

00:08:56.210 --> 00:08:58.100
you start running
out of your sick days

00:08:58.100 --> 00:09:00.410
and you have an
inability of keeping

00:09:00.410 --> 00:09:02.700
your financial viability.

00:09:02.700 --> 00:09:03.200
Eric?

00:09:03.200 --> 00:09:03.860
ERIC SCHNEIDER: Great.

00:09:03.860 --> 00:09:04.190
Thank you.

00:09:04.190 --> 00:09:05.170
And I'll take the next slide.

00:09:05.170 --> 00:09:07.160
BOB BLENDON: It's not
exactly great, but it's.

00:09:07.160 --> 00:09:08.076
ERIC SCHNEIDER: Well--

00:09:08.076 --> 00:09:10.290
MARGOT SANGER-KATZ: So tell
us, aside from finances,

00:09:10.290 --> 00:09:12.160
like how's the care that
this population is getting?

00:09:12.160 --> 00:09:13.580
ERIC SCHNEIDER: --yeah, so
I want to turn to that now.

00:09:13.580 --> 00:09:15.930
But first I want to say
it's great to be back here.

00:09:15.930 --> 00:09:19.160
I've taught at the school and
done research here since 1997,

00:09:19.160 --> 00:09:21.260
and joined the Commonwealth
Fund four years ago.

00:09:21.260 --> 00:09:23.090
It's exciting to be
working with Bob again,

00:09:23.090 --> 00:09:25.690
and to see so many colleagues
and friends in the audience.

00:09:25.690 --> 00:09:28.760
What I want to turn to
next on the next slide is

00:09:28.760 --> 00:09:30.736
this issue that really
dates back to my arrival

00:09:30.736 --> 00:09:32.360
at the Harvard School
of Public Health,

00:09:32.360 --> 00:09:35.560
which was the Institute of
Medicine began to publish

00:09:35.560 --> 00:09:39.030
a series of three reports--

00:09:39.030 --> 00:09:44.140
To Err is Human, about safety,
Crossing the Quality Chasm,

00:09:44.140 --> 00:09:46.930
about the quality
of care, and Report

00:09:46.930 --> 00:09:50.020
on Disparities, racial and
ethnic disparities in care.

00:09:50.020 --> 00:09:54.340
And that's 20 years ago now,
and what our survey has revealed

00:09:54.340 --> 00:09:56.380
is that, for this
population, we've

00:09:56.380 --> 00:09:59.050
actually made remarkably
little progress

00:09:59.050 --> 00:10:00.880
in tackling some of
the problems that

00:10:00.880 --> 00:10:03.010
were outlined in those reports.

00:10:03.010 --> 00:10:07.360
The other thing I wanted to
mention here is that about 56%

00:10:07.360 --> 00:10:12.790
of this group has emotional
problems, anxiety,

00:10:12.790 --> 00:10:16.720
or depression attributable
to their illness.

00:10:16.720 --> 00:10:19.090
And people who may not
have started out that way

00:10:19.090 --> 00:10:21.520
often fall into a
sort of vicious circle

00:10:21.520 --> 00:10:24.400
on that front, as
well as the financial.

00:10:24.400 --> 00:10:29.320
So the next-- sorry, this slide
shows that about 61% of people

00:10:29.320 --> 00:10:33.040
in this population experience
one or more problems that we

00:10:33.040 --> 00:10:36.040
identify, that actually were
identified by the original

00:10:36.040 --> 00:10:38.370
Institute of Medicine
report as problems--

00:10:38.370 --> 00:10:43.240
poor care coordination, a lack
of clarity about services,

00:10:43.240 --> 00:10:45.640
and a lack of
responsiveness of staff

00:10:45.640 --> 00:10:48.440
to the needs of those people.

00:10:48.440 --> 00:10:50.830
And you can see that
those range-- you know,

00:10:50.830 --> 00:10:53.890
it's one in five
or one in four who

00:10:53.890 --> 00:10:55.810
are experiencing each
of those, or reporting

00:10:55.810 --> 00:10:58.220
each of those issues.

00:10:58.220 --> 00:11:02.740
The other issue that comes up
on this slide is patient safety.

00:11:02.740 --> 00:11:05.260
23% of the people
in this survey are

00:11:05.260 --> 00:11:08.510
reporting that they experienced
serious medical errors.

00:11:08.510 --> 00:11:10.210
That's a high rate.

00:11:10.210 --> 00:11:13.750
Not entirely unexpected because
it's a complex population,

00:11:13.750 --> 00:11:15.655
but we have to probably
do better on that.

00:11:15.655 --> 00:11:18.640
So I'll take the next slide.

00:11:18.640 --> 00:11:23.650
I'm just going to sort of pivot
to the solution side of this,

00:11:23.650 --> 00:11:26.110
and give a little frame in
terms of our conclusions

00:11:26.110 --> 00:11:27.550
about what's needed here.

00:11:27.550 --> 00:11:29.110
And this is really
based on the needs

00:11:29.110 --> 00:11:32.410
that patients
experienced and reported.

00:11:32.410 --> 00:11:34.870
Up until the last 20
years, many people

00:11:34.870 --> 00:11:38.320
have focused more on the
delivery system side.

00:11:38.320 --> 00:11:40.990
And as I just said, the
delivery system side

00:11:40.990 --> 00:11:42.950
is not doing what
it needs to do.

00:11:42.950 --> 00:11:46.120
But this survey was an
attempt to actually report

00:11:46.120 --> 00:11:47.770
on the user needs,
the experience

00:11:47.770 --> 00:11:50.390
of these vulnerable populations.

00:11:50.390 --> 00:11:55.510
So the first strategy, area of
strategies, that we identified

00:11:55.510 --> 00:11:58.690
is the issue of building
behavioral health capacity

00:11:58.690 --> 00:12:01.720
to manage behavioral
health needs of this really

00:12:01.720 --> 00:12:03.860
challenged population.

00:12:03.860 --> 00:12:07.390
The second is the issue
of assessing and then

00:12:07.390 --> 00:12:10.120
addressing the social
needs that people

00:12:10.120 --> 00:12:13.940
have-- housing, transportation,
nutritional needs.

00:12:13.940 --> 00:12:18.340
Those are unmet in many in
our survey, for many people.

00:12:18.340 --> 00:12:20.350
The third is to
make coordination

00:12:20.350 --> 00:12:23.470
of care a priority.

00:12:23.470 --> 00:12:25.120
People talk about
care coordination.

00:12:25.120 --> 00:12:26.745
There have been a
lot of federal effort

00:12:26.745 --> 00:12:29.080
to try to bring about care
coordination in the system.

00:12:29.080 --> 00:12:31.370
But there really is
still a high level

00:12:31.370 --> 00:12:34.300
of reporting that the
care is not coordinated,

00:12:34.300 --> 00:12:36.430
and that primary
care in particular

00:12:36.430 --> 00:12:40.760
is not able to solve this
problem yet for most people.

00:12:40.760 --> 00:12:43.120
And then the fourth
is the issue of making

00:12:43.120 --> 00:12:46.390
care more affordable to avoid
the sort of vicious cycle

00:12:46.390 --> 00:12:48.590
that Bob pointed out.

00:12:48.590 --> 00:12:51.254
So with that, I'm going to
turn it over to Bob Master.

00:12:51.254 --> 00:12:52.170
BOB MASTER: Thank you.

00:12:52.170 --> 00:12:57.310
So what I think I
can talk about is

00:12:57.310 --> 00:13:00.550
what about all of
these issues in people

00:13:00.550 --> 00:13:01.780
with additional challenges?

00:13:01.780 --> 00:13:04.450
Low income challenges,
what we now

00:13:04.450 --> 00:13:07.180
call social determinants
of health challenges,

00:13:07.180 --> 00:13:11.770
and people who in fact probably
have the best insurance

00:13:11.770 --> 00:13:15.580
you can have when you put
Medicare and Medicaid together.

00:13:15.580 --> 00:13:18.350
You don't have the
financial issues,

00:13:18.350 --> 00:13:20.620
but you have a care
delivery system

00:13:20.620 --> 00:13:25.780
that is hopelessly
in need of redesign

00:13:25.780 --> 00:13:28.400
to more effectively
provide care.

00:13:28.400 --> 00:13:30.700
So what are the
clinical characteristics

00:13:30.700 --> 00:13:32.530
of this population?

00:13:32.530 --> 00:13:36.550
And it's heterogeneous, but
clearly, as we talked about,

00:13:36.550 --> 00:13:40.540
you have one or more
significant chronic illnesses

00:13:40.540 --> 00:13:43.332
that have very low thresholds
to hospitalization.

00:13:43.332 --> 00:13:45.040
And we'll come back
to the hospital part,

00:13:45.040 --> 00:13:48.550
because that's a part
of the downward spiral.

00:13:48.550 --> 00:13:50.500
You have very high
prevalence of people

00:13:50.500 --> 00:13:55.270
that have long-term service
and support needs, that are not

00:13:55.270 --> 00:13:57.940
fully independent and
may be fully dependent

00:13:57.940 --> 00:13:59.367
and everything
along the spectrum.

00:13:59.367 --> 00:14:01.450
And whether that's a frail
elder or whether that's

00:14:01.450 --> 00:14:03.940
a younger person,
or even a child

00:14:03.940 --> 00:14:07.930
or adolescent with significant
disabilities, that adds to it.

00:14:07.930 --> 00:14:10.840
As Eric said, behavioral
health prevalence

00:14:10.840 --> 00:14:14.950
is extraordinarily high,
and integration is just

00:14:14.950 --> 00:14:16.990
the beginning.

00:14:16.990 --> 00:14:20.530
What is really
needed, and if we're

00:14:20.530 --> 00:14:23.230
going to prevent
that downward spiral

00:14:23.230 --> 00:14:26.410
of recurrent
hospitalizations, 95%

00:14:26.410 --> 00:14:29.660
through the emergency room
because of the low thresholds,

00:14:29.660 --> 00:14:32.925
and each of the spiral
leads to more transitions--

00:14:32.925 --> 00:14:35.250
it's in the transitions
where you have

00:14:35.250 --> 00:14:39.060
the problems and the errors--

00:14:39.060 --> 00:14:42.930
you're going to need an
absolute redesign of what

00:14:42.930 --> 00:14:46.800
is done in addition to
the need for coordination.

00:14:46.800 --> 00:14:50.190
It isn't coordinating
all the pieces here,

00:14:50.190 --> 00:14:52.680
we have to change what is
happening in those pieces.

00:14:52.680 --> 00:14:54.169
And we can talk
about that later.

00:14:54.169 --> 00:14:56.460
MARGOT SANGER-KATZ: Toyin,
I know you guys at CityBlock

00:14:56.460 --> 00:14:58.410
are treating this
population who are

00:14:58.410 --> 00:14:59.861
facing both these
medical and some

00:14:59.861 --> 00:15:01.110
of these financial challenges.

00:15:01.110 --> 00:15:02.610
Can you just talk
to us a little bit

00:15:02.610 --> 00:15:04.235
about how it looks
close to the ground?

00:15:04.235 --> 00:15:04.984
TOYIN AJAYI: Sure.

00:15:04.984 --> 00:15:06.450
And first just to
commend you all,

00:15:06.450 --> 00:15:07.950
thank you so much
for this research.

00:15:07.950 --> 00:15:12.000
It's just so important
to start to quantify

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:15.900
how significant these financial
barriers can be for people

00:15:15.900 --> 00:15:17.070
with serious illness.

00:15:17.070 --> 00:15:19.470
It gives voice and
data to what we

00:15:19.470 --> 00:15:21.340
see in our clinical practice.

00:15:21.340 --> 00:15:23.970
And I think the
key things to note

00:15:23.970 --> 00:15:25.890
in real life, the
population that we're

00:15:25.890 --> 00:15:29.700
serving is that this manifests
both in the financial burden

00:15:29.700 --> 00:15:33.600
that you articulated, but also
in a whole host of continually

00:15:33.600 --> 00:15:35.820
hidden costs, cost
to the patient

00:15:35.820 --> 00:15:38.100
and to the family
that are essentially

00:15:38.100 --> 00:15:40.150
invisible to the
health care system.

00:15:40.150 --> 00:15:42.660
And so when I see my
patients in practice,

00:15:42.660 --> 00:15:44.760
not only do we ask
about and do we

00:15:44.760 --> 00:15:48.390
see the financial costs of care
in the form of particularly

00:15:48.390 --> 00:15:51.270
pharmaceutical costs, but
also have to pay attention

00:15:51.270 --> 00:15:53.370
to the opportunity costs.

00:15:53.370 --> 00:15:55.620
And so when you're talking
about a population of folks

00:15:55.620 --> 00:15:59.280
like the folks who we
serve, who have insurance--

00:15:59.280 --> 00:16:01.620
and by and large,
as Bob described,

00:16:01.620 --> 00:16:03.810
this is probably the best
insurance you can get.

00:16:03.810 --> 00:16:07.600
It's Medicaid, or it's
Medicare, or it's both.

00:16:07.600 --> 00:16:09.900
These are folks, though,
for whom their time is one

00:16:09.900 --> 00:16:11.890
of the most valuable assets.

00:16:11.890 --> 00:16:16.770
And what we don't capture
yet is the opportunity cost

00:16:16.770 --> 00:16:18.840
of being seriously ill.

00:16:18.840 --> 00:16:21.792
So you're asking people
to take time off work.

00:16:21.792 --> 00:16:24.000
If they're working, that's
cash out of their pockets.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:25.375
If they're an
hourly wage worker,

00:16:25.375 --> 00:16:26.550
it's pretty significant.

00:16:26.550 --> 00:16:28.560
We're asking people to
pay for transportation

00:16:28.560 --> 00:16:30.510
to get to the appointment.

00:16:30.510 --> 00:16:34.200
We're asking people to pay for
child care while they're sick

00:16:34.200 --> 00:16:36.960
or while they're accessing
additional services.

00:16:36.960 --> 00:16:40.260
That recurrent cycle continues
to exacerbate the costs

00:16:40.260 --> 00:16:41.820
in that household.

00:16:41.820 --> 00:16:45.630
Additionally, as some folks have
already started to describe,

00:16:45.630 --> 00:16:48.600
the barriers to addressing
all of the other needs

00:16:48.600 --> 00:16:50.910
a person has in their
home and in their life

00:16:50.910 --> 00:16:54.229
in order to access effective
medical care can be huge.

00:16:54.229 --> 00:16:56.520
If you're trying to make a
decision between whether you

00:16:56.520 --> 00:17:00.960
pay $400 for a copay for your
insulin or if you're behind

00:17:00.960 --> 00:17:04.310
on all of your other bills--
your rent, your utility bills--

00:17:04.310 --> 00:17:07.230
it's understandable why
people make rational decisions

00:17:07.230 --> 00:17:09.060
not to access health care.

00:17:09.060 --> 00:17:11.970
And yet to the providers
in the health care system,

00:17:11.970 --> 00:17:16.170
we know that often asking
people about financial burdens

00:17:16.170 --> 00:17:18.540
in their lives is taboo.

00:17:18.540 --> 00:17:21.060
We feel like our job is to
provide the best medical care

00:17:21.060 --> 00:17:22.560
and the best medical
recommendations

00:17:22.560 --> 00:17:24.210
regardless of our
ability to pay,

00:17:24.210 --> 00:17:26.220
and regardless of
people's incomes.

00:17:26.220 --> 00:17:29.640
So recognizing that your
financial status plays

00:17:29.640 --> 00:17:31.800
a role in health and
well-being is something

00:17:31.800 --> 00:17:34.000
that doctors typically
aren't trained to do,

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:36.208
and it's something that the
health care system is not

00:17:36.208 --> 00:17:37.110
oriented to do.

00:17:37.110 --> 00:17:39.860
We find that, in our population,
not asking those questions

00:17:39.860 --> 00:17:41.732
should be tantamount
to medical malpractice,

00:17:41.732 --> 00:17:44.190
because if you're asking someone
to do something that means

00:17:44.190 --> 00:17:46.740
they don't feed their children
or clothe their children,

00:17:46.740 --> 00:17:49.110
or asking them to make
choices and take time out

00:17:49.110 --> 00:17:50.940
of their day in ways
that disadvantage

00:17:50.940 --> 00:17:54.210
them in other parts of their
lives, we are doing them harm.

00:17:54.210 --> 00:17:56.982
And we need to be really
cognizant of that, as well.

00:17:56.982 --> 00:17:58.440
MARGOT SANGER-KATZ:
So in a moment,

00:17:58.440 --> 00:18:00.420
I want to talk more
about solutions

00:18:00.420 --> 00:18:02.190
to try to improve
some of these problems

00:18:02.190 --> 00:18:04.110
that we have
identified, but first I

00:18:04.110 --> 00:18:07.500
want another video clip
about a program that

00:18:07.500 --> 00:18:09.750
is trying to do that, called
the Guided Care program.

00:18:09.750 --> 00:18:12.790
And this clip comes from
the Commonwealth Fund.

00:18:12.790 --> 00:18:14.910
SPEAKER 2: When we have
a doctor's appointment,

00:18:14.910 --> 00:18:16.530
she'll go there with us.

00:18:16.530 --> 00:18:20.550
And she'll sit there and listen
to what the doctor has to say.

00:18:20.550 --> 00:18:22.660
SPEAKER 3: It's been
wonderful having her.

00:18:22.660 --> 00:18:26.072
Gives me a sense of security.

00:18:26.072 --> 00:18:27.780
SPEAKER 4: I think
the biggest challenges

00:18:27.780 --> 00:18:30.300
they face medically
is just trying

00:18:30.300 --> 00:18:32.790
to be as healthy as they
can within their limiting

00:18:32.790 --> 00:18:34.020
conditions.

00:18:34.020 --> 00:18:35.790
As a guided care
nurse, what I try to do

00:18:35.790 --> 00:18:39.060
is give them ways to
feel more confident,

00:18:39.060 --> 00:18:41.950
and to have them do their own
health care or their own med

00:18:41.950 --> 00:18:43.860
setup, but then double
check to give them

00:18:43.860 --> 00:18:45.985
that comfort that they know
they're doing it right.

00:18:45.985 --> 00:18:49.380
Part of my role is seeing
them in their homes,

00:18:49.380 --> 00:18:51.370
going to office
visits with them,

00:18:51.370 --> 00:18:52.745
doing telephone
calls in between.

00:18:52.745 --> 00:18:54.150
Yeah, hi, this is Patti.

00:18:54.150 --> 00:18:57.367
I'm just calling to see how your
medication is working for you.

00:18:57.367 --> 00:18:58.950
We found that guided
care really helps

00:18:58.950 --> 00:19:00.930
in those transitional
areas, because that

00:19:00.930 --> 00:19:03.440
tends to be when patients
will fall through the cracks.

00:19:03.440 --> 00:19:06.340
If the patient is hospitalized,
I see them at the hospital.

00:19:06.340 --> 00:19:09.270
If they're discharged to the
nursing home, I go there.

00:19:09.270 --> 00:19:12.410
My biggest role is to guide
them through wherever they are,

00:19:12.410 --> 00:19:15.600
be it at home, at the
office, at the hospital,

00:19:15.600 --> 00:19:18.690
and make sure that their
care is transitioned

00:19:18.690 --> 00:19:19.892
and there's no errors made.

00:19:19.892 --> 00:19:21.600
MARGOT SANGER-KATZ:
So Eric, I'm curious,

00:19:21.600 --> 00:19:24.016
you obviously know the most
about this particular program.

00:19:24.016 --> 00:19:25.680
And I'm wondering
whether you think

00:19:25.680 --> 00:19:27.510
this program or other
programs like it

00:19:27.510 --> 00:19:29.130
can start to make a dent
in some of the problems

00:19:29.130 --> 00:19:30.150
that we've just
been talking about.

00:19:30.150 --> 00:19:31.025
ERIC SCHNEIDER: Yeah.

00:19:31.025 --> 00:19:34.810
I would love to get Bob and
Toyin's opinion on this, too,

00:19:34.810 --> 00:19:37.470
but it really does
illustrate the need

00:19:37.470 --> 00:19:40.680
to move care into the home-based
setting, into the community,

00:19:40.680 --> 00:19:41.800
as much as possible.

00:19:41.800 --> 00:19:44.590
We really haven't pushed the
envelope in terms of that.

00:19:44.590 --> 00:19:48.180
And I think I just want to
reiterate Bob's point that--

00:19:48.180 --> 00:19:49.524
this Bob--

00:19:49.524 --> 00:19:50.448
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:50.448 --> 00:19:53.154
MARGOT SANGER-KATZ: I
know, we're surrounded.

00:19:53.154 --> 00:19:55.320
ERIC SCHNEIDER: --that it's
not enough to coordinate

00:19:55.320 --> 00:19:57.640
the existing building
blocks of the system.

00:19:57.640 --> 00:20:00.090
We really actually need
to innovate and redesign

00:20:00.090 --> 00:20:03.360
the care to deliver
it in the home

00:20:03.360 --> 00:20:06.960
to address a lot of the other
issues that one can see.

00:20:06.960 --> 00:20:08.520
I've done home
visits, one can see

00:20:08.520 --> 00:20:12.280
these issues that will never
come up in a clinic setting.

00:20:12.280 --> 00:20:16.310
And so I think that's
really important.

00:20:16.310 --> 00:20:17.310
BOB MASTER: I can start.

00:20:17.310 --> 00:20:19.050
By the way, I
think after working

00:20:19.050 --> 00:20:21.316
with Toyin for
over six years, we

00:20:21.316 --> 00:20:22.815
can complete each
other's sentences.

00:20:22.815 --> 00:20:23.640
[LAUGHTER]

00:20:23.640 --> 00:20:28.510
And maybe we should do this
as a team without question.

00:20:28.510 --> 00:20:31.960
But if we just look at
those building blocks--

00:20:31.960 --> 00:20:34.140
first of all, what are
the redesign elements?

00:20:34.140 --> 00:20:37.050
And I really do want to start
with the extraordinary work

00:20:37.050 --> 00:20:40.350
that was really done
as part of the ACA

00:20:40.350 --> 00:20:45.090
to really try to scale a
systems of care and change

00:20:45.090 --> 00:20:50.850
that really was neglected
for decades ever

00:20:50.850 --> 00:20:55.220
since the onset of
Medicare and Medicaid.

00:20:55.220 --> 00:20:57.540
And that was the beginning
of global payments

00:20:57.540 --> 00:21:01.140
where a clinical organization
with the appropriate risk

00:21:01.140 --> 00:21:04.410
adjustment could have complete
responsibility over all

00:21:04.410 --> 00:21:07.320
of the benefits and services
of medical care, hospital

00:21:07.320 --> 00:21:09.510
care, pharmacy,
and long-term care

00:21:09.510 --> 00:21:11.100
that you could
bring to a person.

00:21:11.100 --> 00:21:13.770
And that allows you
to re-imagine care.

00:21:13.770 --> 00:21:17.040
So fee for service,
piecemeal care

00:21:17.040 --> 00:21:20.760
where a physician in an office
is seeing people in 15 minute

00:21:20.760 --> 00:21:22.450
visits don't work.

00:21:22.450 --> 00:21:25.830
And the next thing that
is really required in that

00:21:25.830 --> 00:21:27.910
is to re-imagine primary care.

00:21:27.910 --> 00:21:32.490
And that would be not just a
doctor in an office, and not

00:21:32.490 --> 00:21:35.490
just 3% to 4% of the
total medical spend

00:21:35.490 --> 00:21:37.710
going to primary
care, but in fact,

00:21:37.710 --> 00:21:40.770
an interdisciplinary team
that may look different

00:21:40.770 --> 00:21:42.210
for different populations.

00:21:42.210 --> 00:21:44.610
And that would be the doctor,
the nurse practitioner

00:21:44.610 --> 00:21:46.470
for people with
physical disabilities,

00:21:46.470 --> 00:21:49.770
integrated physical therapy
and occupational therapy,

00:21:49.770 --> 00:21:53.190
and durable medical equipment
for the integrated behavioral

00:21:53.190 --> 00:21:55.590
health to reiterate
the importance of that

00:21:55.590 --> 00:21:57.150
in practices.

00:21:57.150 --> 00:22:00.510
And you're now then
talking about 10% to 12%

00:22:00.510 --> 00:22:04.860
of the pie that has
to go to primary care.

00:22:04.860 --> 00:22:07.960
And until we resource
that correctly,

00:22:07.960 --> 00:22:10.170
and until we move to global
payment arrangements,

00:22:10.170 --> 00:22:12.660
you're not going to
be able to do that.

00:22:12.660 --> 00:22:16.230
You then have to build
what we call elasticity

00:22:16.230 --> 00:22:18.030
into the system in primary care.

00:22:21.510 --> 00:22:23.910
Toyin and I go to
work in the morning.

00:22:23.910 --> 00:22:27.120
Most physicians are booked
from 8:00 in the morning

00:22:27.120 --> 00:22:29.610
until who knows
when in the evening.

00:22:29.610 --> 00:22:32.940
And yet, if you have
people with low thresholds

00:22:32.940 --> 00:22:35.866
to problems that
are going to occur,

00:22:35.866 --> 00:22:38.340
how do they receive that care?

00:22:38.340 --> 00:22:41.340
In the United States today, it's
the ambulance and the emergency

00:22:41.340 --> 00:22:42.670
room.

00:22:42.670 --> 00:22:44.520
So thinking about elasticity.

00:22:44.520 --> 00:22:46.530
If you have a
frail elder at home

00:22:46.530 --> 00:22:48.210
or a person with
disabilities, you've

00:22:48.210 --> 00:22:50.010
got to get that
assessment and you've

00:22:50.010 --> 00:22:52.410
got to move it into the home.

00:22:52.410 --> 00:22:55.320
In fact, for people with
physical disabilities

00:22:55.320 --> 00:22:58.680
who rely on the
publicly funded ride,

00:22:58.680 --> 00:23:00.510
they can't get to
a doctor's office

00:23:00.510 --> 00:23:03.360
immediately because you
got to have a 24 to 48

00:23:03.360 --> 00:23:06.030
hour appointment
window to do that.

00:23:06.030 --> 00:23:11.770
So it's now primary care as
a service and not a building.

00:23:11.770 --> 00:23:16.500
And seeing people as needed
and not by appointment.

00:23:16.500 --> 00:23:19.920
And then comes the
second and third stage.

00:23:19.920 --> 00:23:22.840
How do we then move into
what we call the primary care

00:23:22.840 --> 00:23:26.880
whitespace, which is
what happens after hours

00:23:26.880 --> 00:23:29.070
when somebody is sick
and a physician takes

00:23:29.070 --> 00:23:32.070
that call at midnight,
and you can't figure out

00:23:32.070 --> 00:23:33.900
whether this can
take two aspirins

00:23:33.900 --> 00:23:37.140
and we'll see you tomorrow
or you're really sick,

00:23:37.140 --> 00:23:39.120
we got to get you in now.

00:23:39.120 --> 00:23:40.830
Most of it falls in
the middle where you

00:23:40.830 --> 00:23:42.040
don't know what's happening.

00:23:42.040 --> 00:23:45.360
And by default, this
frail elder or a person

00:23:45.360 --> 00:23:49.930
with risk for hospitalizations
goes to the emergency room.

00:23:49.930 --> 00:23:52.740
What do you do there in
terms of system change?

00:23:52.740 --> 00:23:59.250
And there is some interesting
work with advanced life support

00:23:59.250 --> 00:24:02.220
clinicians that can do
this kind of response

00:24:02.220 --> 00:24:05.010
as part of a primary care team.

00:24:05.010 --> 00:24:06.510
And the last-- and
I'll stop here--

00:24:06.510 --> 00:24:10.020
is the redesign of how you care
for people in the hospital.

00:24:10.020 --> 00:24:13.920
In one sentence, you're moving
primary care and continuity

00:24:13.920 --> 00:24:16.740
into the hospital.

00:24:16.740 --> 00:24:21.460
And so when a person needs it,
they've got their teams there.

00:24:21.460 --> 00:24:22.960
And I'll stop.

00:24:22.960 --> 00:24:25.342
MARGOT SANGER-KATZ: So Toyin,
I see a lot of nodding.

00:24:25.342 --> 00:24:26.550
TOYIN AJAYI: So much nodding.

00:24:26.550 --> 00:24:28.538
[LAUGHTER]

00:24:28.538 --> 00:24:30.390
MARGOT SANGER-KATZ:
I'm curious, as you

00:24:30.390 --> 00:24:33.280
think about these opportunities
for improving coordination

00:24:33.280 --> 00:24:34.960
for this population
that's really sick.

00:24:34.960 --> 00:24:36.520
People have a lot
of illnesses who

00:24:36.520 --> 00:24:40.540
have been hospitalized a lot,
who have lot of medical needs.

00:24:40.540 --> 00:24:43.780
Are the strategies--
do they carry over

00:24:43.780 --> 00:24:45.910
to those of us who
are normally healthy,

00:24:45.910 --> 00:24:48.190
but maybe have a crisis
every once in a while?

00:24:48.190 --> 00:24:49.930
Or does it feel like
a unique problem

00:24:49.930 --> 00:24:51.694
that needs a unique
set of situations?

00:24:51.694 --> 00:24:53.860
I'm just wondering how much
is this a good metaphor?

00:24:53.860 --> 00:24:55.210
If we figured out how
to solve these people,

00:24:55.210 --> 00:24:56.890
then we're going to
translate it over here.

00:24:56.890 --> 00:24:59.014
How much of it is, OK,
let's just do one thing here

00:24:59.014 --> 00:24:59.927
and one thing there.

00:24:59.927 --> 00:25:02.010
TOYIN AJAYI: I think it's
a really great question.

00:25:02.010 --> 00:25:05.260
So the way that
we have typically

00:25:05.260 --> 00:25:08.260
used innovation in
health care in particular

00:25:08.260 --> 00:25:11.157
has been that we've
solved for the healthy.

00:25:11.157 --> 00:25:13.240
If you think about the
typical primary care model,

00:25:13.240 --> 00:25:16.150
for example, it works
great if you're in your 20s

00:25:16.150 --> 00:25:18.114
and you don't have a
lot of medical needs,

00:25:18.114 --> 00:25:19.780
and you can afford
to take time off work

00:25:19.780 --> 00:25:21.863
to go see a primary care
doctor, and you can wait,

00:25:21.863 --> 00:25:23.950
and you can come back,
and pay the copay,

00:25:23.950 --> 00:25:25.617
and get your once
a year physical.

00:25:25.617 --> 00:25:26.200
It works fine.

00:25:26.200 --> 00:25:27.310
It's not perfect.

00:25:27.310 --> 00:25:29.070
It could be better,
but it works fine.

00:25:29.070 --> 00:25:30.970
And the innovation
in primary care

00:25:30.970 --> 00:25:34.420
largely has been to try to
make that interaction more

00:25:34.420 --> 00:25:36.850
seamless for people who
are relatively healthy

00:25:36.850 --> 00:25:39.130
and have resources.

00:25:39.130 --> 00:25:39.880
That doesn't work.

00:25:39.880 --> 00:25:42.504
It's not going to trickle
down to people who are sick.

00:25:42.504 --> 00:25:44.170
It's not going to
trickle down to people

00:25:44.170 --> 00:25:46.030
with complex needs
for all of the reasons

00:25:46.030 --> 00:25:48.730
that Bob described when
you talk about the 24/7

00:25:48.730 --> 00:25:53.170
nature of their need for access
to high quality health care.

00:25:53.170 --> 00:25:57.940
That said, however, any single
one of us who is healthy today

00:25:57.940 --> 00:26:03.430
is, as we know, a unfortunate
accident, a catastrophe,

00:26:03.430 --> 00:26:06.920
an undiagnosed cancer
away from being sick.

00:26:06.920 --> 00:26:08.950
And the data from
this study shows

00:26:08.950 --> 00:26:11.440
that if that happens, no
matter where you start,

00:26:11.440 --> 00:26:14.380
if you're insured or not,
the risk that that pushes you

00:26:14.380 --> 00:26:16.620
into poverty is so great.

00:26:16.620 --> 00:26:20.110
So suddenly, we have
a frame in which

00:26:20.110 --> 00:26:22.450
the safety net system that
we're building actually

00:26:22.450 --> 00:26:23.590
may serve any one of us.

00:26:23.590 --> 00:26:26.530
Any person in this country
who is going to age

00:26:26.530 --> 00:26:29.860
and be sick over time,
which as the population ages

00:26:29.860 --> 00:26:33.190
and as we start to prevent more
and more diseases until later

00:26:33.190 --> 00:26:35.410
into our adulthood, is
going to be most of us.

00:26:35.410 --> 00:26:37.570
As we got into our 60s
and 70s, the likelihood

00:26:37.570 --> 00:26:40.540
that we're living with chronic
conditions is incredibly high.

00:26:40.540 --> 00:26:42.040
And the likelihood
that one of those

00:26:42.040 --> 00:26:45.100
makes us have to seek hospital
care and expensive drug

00:26:45.100 --> 00:26:48.770
treatments that push us into
poverty is also quite high.

00:26:48.770 --> 00:26:51.460
But when we build solutions,
we have to build intensely

00:26:51.460 --> 00:26:53.650
for that population.

00:26:53.650 --> 00:26:56.200
And the lessons will
trickle up, if you will,

00:26:56.200 --> 00:26:59.550
to people who are less sick
who need less of the services.

00:26:59.550 --> 00:27:01.475
They may require
fewer of the tools

00:27:01.475 --> 00:27:05.460
in the toolkit in a much
less frequent fashion.

00:27:05.460 --> 00:27:07.600
But we need to have
them there because it

00:27:07.600 --> 00:27:08.600
could be any one of us.

00:27:08.600 --> 00:27:12.280
And so when we think about
really focusing innovation,

00:27:12.280 --> 00:27:14.290
putting together
the best teams we

00:27:14.290 --> 00:27:17.500
can around technology, around
operational design, logistics,

00:27:17.500 --> 00:27:22.826
24/7 access to care, [INAUDIBLE]
in service of this use case.

00:27:22.826 --> 00:27:24.850
Our hypothesis,
though, is that as we

00:27:24.850 --> 00:27:26.890
start to push those
tools out, they

00:27:26.890 --> 00:27:30.130
will become in service of folks
who are less needed today,

00:27:30.130 --> 00:27:32.625
but over time they
become high risk.

00:27:32.625 --> 00:27:34.000
MARGOT SANGER-KATZ:
I just wanted

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:36.790
to make sure that we
circled back to Bob's slides

00:27:36.790 --> 00:27:38.410
about some of the
financial stresses

00:27:38.410 --> 00:27:41.890
that people face because those
really did stick out to me.

00:27:41.890 --> 00:27:44.800
And I feel they connect to a
growing body of research that

00:27:44.800 --> 00:27:48.010
shows that not only
are we seeing more

00:27:48.010 --> 00:27:51.070
people with insurance that has
high cost sharing that exposes

00:27:51.070 --> 00:27:53.800
them to a lot of out-of-pocket
costs even if they are insured,

00:27:53.800 --> 00:27:55.780
but also growing
evidence that being sick

00:27:55.780 --> 00:27:59.146
has other financial consequences
for people because if you can't

00:27:59.146 --> 00:28:00.770
work-- even if you
don't lose your job,

00:28:00.770 --> 00:28:02.170
if you have to take time
off, you have to cut back

00:28:02.170 --> 00:28:04.294
on your hours, if you have
disability that makes it

00:28:04.294 --> 00:28:05.710
hard to do the
same kind of work,

00:28:05.710 --> 00:28:09.970
that losing income can be an
additional financial challenge

00:28:09.970 --> 00:28:11.350
associated with being sick.

00:28:11.350 --> 00:28:13.900
And so I'm just wondering
how should we think

00:28:13.900 --> 00:28:17.140
about this group of problems?

00:28:17.140 --> 00:28:19.066
Is health insurance good enough?

00:28:19.066 --> 00:28:20.440
What can we do to
make it better?

00:28:20.440 --> 00:28:24.460
Do we need other kinds of wrap
around insurance for people

00:28:24.460 --> 00:28:27.250
so that when they get sick they
don't get pushed into poverty

00:28:27.250 --> 00:28:28.390
as Toyin described?

00:28:28.390 --> 00:28:29.190
ROBERT BLENDON: So I'm
going to surprise you.

00:28:29.190 --> 00:28:30.981
I'm not going to say
it's all very complex.

00:28:30.981 --> 00:28:31.870
[LAUGHTER]

00:28:31.870 --> 00:28:35.740
So first, all you have to do
is turn on the TV, and look,

00:28:35.740 --> 00:28:37.750
we're now in the Medicare
enrollment choice.

00:28:37.750 --> 00:28:41.434
And it says, pick the Medicare
wrap around that you need.

00:28:41.434 --> 00:28:42.850
The first thing
out of this survey

00:28:42.850 --> 00:28:47.740
is very few people knew three
years ahead that they would

00:28:47.740 --> 00:28:51.280
have five hospitalizations,
$50,000 of drug bills,

00:28:51.280 --> 00:28:52.570
five doctors.

00:28:52.570 --> 00:28:53.710
They had no idea.

00:28:53.710 --> 00:28:56.380
And we're telling
them to choose a plan.

00:28:56.380 --> 00:28:58.090
Now how can I be
insured and have

00:28:58.090 --> 00:29:00.340
$50,000 of prescription drugs?

00:29:00.340 --> 00:29:01.270
That's easy.

00:29:01.270 --> 00:29:02.830
I bought a drug benefit.

00:29:02.830 --> 00:29:06.190
Except somebody gave me a
drug for cancer or something,

00:29:06.190 --> 00:29:08.980
and that little drug
benefit won't do that.

00:29:08.980 --> 00:29:11.650
And so we're having a
debate for the under 65.

00:29:11.650 --> 00:29:13.654
Let's choose the plan you need.

00:29:13.654 --> 00:29:15.820
There's no reason that you
should have requirements.

00:29:15.820 --> 00:29:17.140
Same thing happened.

00:29:17.140 --> 00:29:18.940
A young adult
choosing has no idea

00:29:18.940 --> 00:29:21.290
they're getting hit by a
car or have a heart attack.

00:29:21.290 --> 00:29:22.300
And so they don't know.

00:29:22.300 --> 00:29:25.390
So what do we need simply is not
what it appears on television.

00:29:25.390 --> 00:29:29.470
Get yourself a counselor to read
the 47 pages of the Medicare

00:29:29.470 --> 00:29:30.310
alternatives.

00:29:30.310 --> 00:29:34.025
No, there has to be a federal
or state agency that certifies.

00:29:34.025 --> 00:29:34.525
Very simple.

00:29:34.525 --> 00:29:35.740
A little star.

00:29:35.740 --> 00:29:37.930
If you buy this plan,
it will cover you

00:29:37.930 --> 00:29:39.550
for your catastrophic illnesses.

00:29:39.550 --> 00:29:41.970
You don't have to read
the other 47 pages.

00:29:41.970 --> 00:29:43.720
And it probably is
going to have to extend

00:29:43.720 --> 00:29:45.100
coverage that isn't there.

00:29:45.100 --> 00:29:48.640
You should not require
people to have to figure out,

00:29:48.640 --> 00:29:50.816
will my cancer be a type one?

00:29:50.816 --> 00:29:52.690
And that will be covered
fully by the policy,

00:29:52.690 --> 00:29:54.400
but a type two isn't fully.

00:29:54.400 --> 00:29:55.820
You're not going to know that.

00:29:55.820 --> 00:29:58.840
So a nice little star
says, don't worry,

00:29:58.840 --> 00:30:00.760
when the ambulance
comes and you're there,

00:30:00.760 --> 00:30:02.470
you have a policy
that will cover it.

00:30:02.470 --> 00:30:03.760
We have no certification.

00:30:03.760 --> 00:30:08.830
Likewise, we need a catastrophic
something for work-related days

00:30:08.830 --> 00:30:09.970
off benefits.

00:30:09.970 --> 00:30:12.340
At some point, it kicks back in.

00:30:12.340 --> 00:30:16.270
And if you really are caring for
somebody needs a lot of care,

00:30:16.270 --> 00:30:19.390
your job has some
protection that after 14

00:30:19.390 --> 00:30:21.430
days of sick days,
they don't fire you.

00:30:21.430 --> 00:30:25.120
And it has to be a requirement
where it kicks in way down.

00:30:25.120 --> 00:30:27.910
But those two things,
an easy certification.

00:30:27.910 --> 00:30:29.980
But please, the
people we surveyed

00:30:29.980 --> 00:30:34.060
could not read a 37
page choice document.

00:30:34.060 --> 00:30:37.390
And that ad which says
we'll get you a reaper

00:30:37.390 --> 00:30:39.900
and we'll work your way
through, that's exactly what

00:30:39.900 --> 00:30:41.170
is not needed.

00:30:41.170 --> 00:30:44.080
What's needed is a
simple certification that

00:30:44.080 --> 00:30:45.910
says, if this happens to you--

00:30:45.910 --> 00:30:49.090
and by the way, if we told you
we were giving a drug benefit,

00:30:49.090 --> 00:30:52.390
the company can't say I'm not
going to pay for this drug.

00:30:52.390 --> 00:30:53.744
It's just not fair to people.

00:30:53.744 --> 00:30:55.660
They have no way of
knowing that they're going

00:30:55.660 --> 00:30:56.951
to have to have a prescription.

00:30:56.951 --> 00:31:00.310
So this is simple, but
I'm a tenured professor.

00:31:00.310 --> 00:31:00.810
[LAUGHTER]

00:31:00.810 --> 00:31:03.143
MARGOT SANGER-KATZ: That
sounds like an expensive system

00:31:03.143 --> 00:31:04.159
what you're describing.

00:31:04.159 --> 00:31:06.700
ROBERT BLENDON: That's why he
does costs and I do protection.

00:31:06.700 --> 00:31:07.895
[LAUGHTER]

00:31:07.895 --> 00:31:09.270
MARGOT SANGER-KATZ:
Do any of you

00:31:09.270 --> 00:31:10.420
other guys have
thoughts about that?

00:31:10.420 --> 00:31:11.637
About this cost problem?

00:31:11.637 --> 00:31:13.720
ROBERT MASTER: Very briefly,
I have to respond now

00:31:13.720 --> 00:31:17.260
that I am a Medicare
beneficiary myself

00:31:17.260 --> 00:31:18.490
and having gone through this.

00:31:18.490 --> 00:31:21.010
And I think I know
more about this world

00:31:21.010 --> 00:31:23.920
than most people having
lived it for decades.

00:31:23.920 --> 00:31:25.720
I won't say how many.

00:31:25.720 --> 00:31:27.580
And this policy decade.

00:31:27.580 --> 00:31:30.550
And it was opaque.

00:31:30.550 --> 00:31:35.760
Absolutely opaque in saying
which drug plan do you pick?

00:31:35.760 --> 00:31:41.270
Which wrap around
Medigap do you pick?

00:31:41.270 --> 00:31:44.860
And I'm saying, oh, my god,
if it's that opaque for me,

00:31:44.860 --> 00:31:46.810
how is it for
people that are not

00:31:46.810 --> 00:31:48.271
in health care in this world?

00:31:48.271 --> 00:31:50.770
MARGOT SANGER-KATZ: I would say
that's the most common email

00:31:50.770 --> 00:31:53.540
that I get from
colleagues or friends.

00:31:53.540 --> 00:31:57.169
Can you help me select
between these options?

00:31:57.169 --> 00:31:58.960
TOYIN AJAYI: If I could
just add one thing.

00:31:58.960 --> 00:32:02.170
This is the quintessential
of market failure, right?

00:32:02.170 --> 00:32:05.686
There is such a lack of
information available to people

00:32:05.686 --> 00:32:07.420
that are making these choices.

00:32:07.420 --> 00:32:09.670
And I think what just
adds insult to injury

00:32:09.670 --> 00:32:11.110
is that this data is available.

00:32:11.110 --> 00:32:14.230
And actually, it's
being used, I would

00:32:14.230 --> 00:32:15.980
argue, not for good
by other agents,

00:32:15.980 --> 00:32:17.230
but in the health care system.

00:32:17.230 --> 00:32:20.830
So you think that health
insurance plans can

00:32:20.830 --> 00:32:23.200
tell by your purchasing
patterns, your demographics,

00:32:23.200 --> 00:32:25.900
and where you live
the likelihood of you

00:32:25.900 --> 00:32:28.270
becoming seriously ill
in the next five years.

00:32:28.270 --> 00:32:30.550
And they do use this to
try to figure out where

00:32:30.550 --> 00:32:31.954
they should market their plans.

00:32:31.954 --> 00:32:34.120
They want to the healthiest
people on their Medicare

00:32:34.120 --> 00:32:36.160
Advantage plans.

00:32:36.160 --> 00:32:39.820
Large retail stores
know exactly when

00:32:39.820 --> 00:32:43.060
you are likely to have a
need for x or y product.

00:32:43.060 --> 00:32:46.990
And that's when miraculously
the ad shows up on your iPhone

00:32:46.990 --> 00:32:50.230
or the flyer comes
through your mailbox.

00:32:50.230 --> 00:32:52.900
We have the data to
help people better

00:32:52.900 --> 00:32:55.990
understand what their risks
are and what the likelihood

00:32:55.990 --> 00:32:58.750
that they're going to
need catastrophic coverage

00:32:58.750 --> 00:33:01.310
and how they should be
prioritizing their resources.

00:33:01.310 --> 00:33:03.190
So even just giving
more transparency

00:33:03.190 --> 00:33:05.730
to that information, some
guiding, some coaching.

00:33:05.730 --> 00:33:08.209
And then I love the idea
of certifying plans.

00:33:08.209 --> 00:33:10.000
That when you know
you're buying something,

00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:12.130
you know what you
can expect from it.

00:33:12.130 --> 00:33:14.530
It's such a fundamental
thing I think

00:33:14.530 --> 00:33:17.590
we can do to help people, in
addition to all of the work

00:33:17.590 --> 00:33:20.500
that we need to do to put
pressure on on the broader

00:33:20.500 --> 00:33:23.200
systems to really ask
what coverage you need

00:33:23.200 --> 00:33:26.290
and what our commitment
to ensuring that when

00:33:26.290 --> 00:33:28.240
we say people have
insurance that they really

00:33:28.240 --> 00:33:29.410
have insurance.

00:33:29.410 --> 00:33:32.800
It feels like there's almost a
nomenclature gap here as well

00:33:32.800 --> 00:33:35.380
because we're not seeing
quite the same thing when

00:33:35.380 --> 00:33:36.867
we say you have
coverage and then

00:33:36.867 --> 00:33:38.950
we find out that actually
your out-of-pocket costs

00:33:38.950 --> 00:33:40.735
are through the roof
and you had no idea.

00:33:40.735 --> 00:33:42.485
ERIC SCHNEIDER: Yeah,
