be that your health insurance
benefits should include

00:37:45.720 --> 00:37:47.636
some stipend for someone
who takes care of you

00:37:47.636 --> 00:37:50.497
if you have a really
serious problem?

00:37:50.497 --> 00:37:52.580
ROBERT MASTER: And you
don't have a Medicaid card?

00:37:52.580 --> 00:37:52.860
MARGOT SANGER-KATZ: Right.

00:37:52.860 --> 00:37:54.910
ROBERT MASTER: Yeah, possibly.

00:37:54.910 --> 00:37:56.355
And it may be very
cost effective

00:37:56.355 --> 00:37:59.470
in the investment in that.

00:37:59.470 --> 00:38:00.986
Absolutely.

00:38:00.986 --> 00:38:02.610
MARGOT SANGER-KATZ:
Any other thoughts?

00:38:02.610 --> 00:38:04.276
TOYIN AJAYI: The other
thing I would add

00:38:04.276 --> 00:38:06.546
is-- and it's not quite
responsive to the question

00:38:06.546 --> 00:38:07.920
because it's not
as much a policy

00:38:07.920 --> 00:38:10.290
lever as it is a
care model lever is

00:38:10.290 --> 00:38:12.030
thinking about social care.

00:38:12.030 --> 00:38:15.120
And so we at City
Block really focus

00:38:15.120 --> 00:38:17.209
on going beyond
screening and referral

00:38:17.209 --> 00:38:18.750
for social determinants,
but thinking

00:38:18.750 --> 00:38:22.440
about social components of
care as a whole thick piece

00:38:22.440 --> 00:38:23.820
of the puzzle.

00:38:23.820 --> 00:38:28.500
And that means asking both who
do you depend on for supports?

00:38:28.500 --> 00:38:30.660
Physical practical,
tangible supports as well as

00:38:30.660 --> 00:38:32.130
emotional supports.

00:38:32.130 --> 00:38:34.110
And also, who depends on you?

00:38:34.110 --> 00:38:35.850
And recognizing
that every person

00:38:35.850 --> 00:38:40.110
is part of a complex ecosystem
of relationships that sometimes

00:38:40.110 --> 00:38:42.810
make them dependent on
another and other times

00:38:42.810 --> 00:38:46.020
allow them to be the
support person for others.

00:38:46.020 --> 00:38:47.850
If we ask those
questions as a matter

00:38:47.850 --> 00:38:50.880
of routine in all of our
health care interactions

00:38:50.880 --> 00:38:54.750
everywhere in the system,
than it necessarily behooves

00:38:54.750 --> 00:38:56.080
us try to act on those.

00:38:56.080 --> 00:38:58.260
And so when you think
about people going home

00:38:58.260 --> 00:39:01.440
from the hospital, if it was
the business of the health care

00:39:01.440 --> 00:39:05.940
system to know that your
daughter is the person who

00:39:05.940 --> 00:39:08.820
really supports you in
getting dressed every morning

00:39:08.820 --> 00:39:12.100
and that she's just taken a new
job out of town or something,

00:39:12.100 --> 00:39:14.400
then we're able to start to
think about what it looks

00:39:14.400 --> 00:39:16.620
like for your discharge
home and what other supports

00:39:16.620 --> 00:39:18.120
we would need to put in place.

00:39:18.120 --> 00:39:21.420
Versus the converse,
recognizing that if we

00:39:21.420 --> 00:39:24.840
have patients, individuals
who are also carers,

00:39:24.840 --> 00:39:25.840
because we can be both.

00:39:25.840 --> 00:39:28.950
We can be seriously ill,
dependent on others,

00:39:28.950 --> 00:39:30.420
and also carers for others.

00:39:30.420 --> 00:39:32.820
The impact on the whole
ecosystem around you

00:39:32.820 --> 00:39:34.410
can be profound.

00:39:34.410 --> 00:39:36.690
So what we're
finding in particular

00:39:36.690 --> 00:39:40.980
when we think about cost is that
interventions on social care

00:39:40.980 --> 00:39:45.240
are cheaper in general
and accrue returns

00:39:45.240 --> 00:39:48.630
across a larger number of people
than a health care intervention

00:39:48.630 --> 00:39:51.097
where you treat a patient and
that patient derives benefit.

00:39:51.097 --> 00:39:52.680
If you're thinking
about, for example,

00:39:52.680 --> 00:39:54.120
food insecure individuals.

00:39:54.120 --> 00:39:57.401
If I had a senior who
didn't have enough food, who

00:39:57.401 --> 00:39:59.400
was dependent on their
daughter or granddaughter

00:39:59.400 --> 00:40:01.920
to help make sure
they ate every day

00:40:01.920 --> 00:40:03.420
and we worked with
them to make them

00:40:03.420 --> 00:40:05.490
less dependent on
that family member,

00:40:05.490 --> 00:40:07.020
we've actually
unlocked capabilities

00:40:07.020 --> 00:40:09.180
across the whole family.

00:40:09.180 --> 00:40:11.650
And that's really a powerful
set of interventions.

00:40:11.650 --> 00:40:13.200
And so thinking
about social care

00:40:13.200 --> 00:40:14.825
both as an understanding
of what people

00:40:14.825 --> 00:40:16.999
social abilities,
their needs are,

00:40:16.999 --> 00:40:18.540
and then addressing
those just as you

00:40:18.540 --> 00:40:21.580
would any other part of
their health care needs

00:40:21.580 --> 00:40:23.580
can be a really powerful
way to start to address

00:40:23.580 --> 00:40:26.865
the burden on caregivers.

00:40:26.865 --> 00:40:30.214
MARGOT SANGER-KATZ: Do we
