enhancement to a care system.

00:41:36.850 --> 00:41:40.700
But it really still starts
with that home-based personal

00:41:40.700 --> 00:41:41.200
capacity.

00:41:41.200 --> 00:41:43.540
How do we move primary
care into the home?

00:41:43.540 --> 00:41:45.680
How do we have a
response to new problems?

00:41:45.680 --> 00:41:49.840
How do we allocate the right
amount of long term services

00:41:49.840 --> 00:41:55.640
and support services
that are needed?

00:41:55.640 --> 00:41:59.620
And then TeleHealth clearly,
I think, can enhance that.

00:41:59.620 --> 00:42:03.210
But in and of itself,
without a system redesign,

00:42:03.210 --> 00:42:04.799
I have problems.

00:42:04.799 --> 00:42:06.340
I don't know, what
do you think Tory?

00:42:06.340 --> 00:42:07.214
TOYIN AJAYI: I agree.

00:42:07.214 --> 00:42:08.600
I mean, of course I agree 100%.

00:42:08.600 --> 00:42:12.220
I mean, I think going back to
the foundational principles

00:42:12.220 --> 00:42:14.920
of what we're trying to solve
for, when we have people

00:42:14.920 --> 00:42:17.680
with serious illness
with multiple competing

00:42:17.680 --> 00:42:22.510
concerns, who also either in
addition to and before they

00:42:22.510 --> 00:42:24.350
became seriously ill,
or as a consequence

00:42:24.350 --> 00:42:27.790
of the serious illness, are also
struggling with social needs,

00:42:27.790 --> 00:42:30.240
that home visit and
that home-based care

00:42:30.240 --> 00:42:34.820
is just catalytic in two ways.

00:42:34.820 --> 00:42:36.610
One, I think the
questioner asked

00:42:36.610 --> 00:42:39.070
about kind of the opportunity
cost, and that's huge.

00:42:39.070 --> 00:42:43.330
It's moving people from
the whole cycle of getting

00:42:43.330 --> 00:42:46.120
into a clinic multiple
times, sometimes even

00:42:46.120 --> 00:42:48.640
multiple times a
week, saves them time

00:42:48.640 --> 00:42:51.770
and allows them to do other
things, which is important.

00:42:51.770 --> 00:42:54.010
But there's also
foundational kind

00:42:54.010 --> 00:42:57.700
of values and trust
building exercise

00:42:57.700 --> 00:43:01.600
that happens when human
being from the care system

00:43:01.600 --> 00:43:03.610
steps foot in
their patients home

00:43:03.610 --> 00:43:06.970
that is just
incredibly powerful.

00:43:06.970 --> 00:43:11.110
It re-balances the
patient-provider relationship.

00:43:11.110 --> 00:43:14.200
You know as a physician
going into a patient's home,

00:43:14.200 --> 00:43:15.920
I wait for them.

00:43:15.920 --> 00:43:17.570
I see them on their own terms.

00:43:17.570 --> 00:43:21.370
I am humbled in their presence,
which is really important when

00:43:21.370 --> 00:43:23.927
I think that this is a
person I want to call me

00:43:23.927 --> 00:43:25.510
instead of going to
the emergency room

00:43:25.510 --> 00:43:26.740
when they're feeling sick.

00:43:26.740 --> 00:43:27.910
They need to trust me.

00:43:27.910 --> 00:43:29.860
And you don't trust
somebody who you

00:43:29.860 --> 00:43:31.600
don't feel like
you can relate to,

00:43:31.600 --> 00:43:34.240
who you don't feel
like is there for you,

00:43:34.240 --> 00:43:35.570
and who doesn't listen to you.

00:43:35.570 --> 00:43:37.720
And so being able to just
establish that foundation

00:43:37.720 --> 00:43:39.220
is so powerful.

00:43:39.220 --> 00:43:41.680
What we found is that
if you layer TeleHealth

00:43:41.680 --> 00:43:43.930
on top of that
trusted relationship,

00:43:43.930 --> 00:43:48.220
you unlock a ton of potential
for the ease of 24/7 access

00:43:48.220 --> 00:43:51.700
and for the ability
to operationally

00:43:51.700 --> 00:43:54.577
kind of scale its type of
very human-centered approach.

00:43:54.577 --> 00:43:55.910
And we do that a couple of ways.

00:43:55.910 --> 00:44:00.820
One is following a series
of really in-depth,

00:44:00.820 --> 00:44:03.556
in-person conversations with
members of the care team,

00:44:03.556 --> 00:44:06.055
we find that our patients are
much more likely to than video

00:44:06.055 --> 00:44:10.210
in, or tele-visit, or
text us, or call us

00:44:10.210 --> 00:44:11.630
when they're having needs.

00:44:11.630 --> 00:44:13.780
The other thing that we
think is really interesting

00:44:13.780 --> 00:44:16.879
is allowing a different
member of the care team--

00:44:16.879 --> 00:44:18.670
we've talked about
interdisciplinary teams.

00:44:18.670 --> 00:44:20.780
Bob Master talked
about this earlier,

00:44:20.780 --> 00:44:22.570
but really thinking
about the power

00:44:22.570 --> 00:44:25.902
of non-clinically licensed
individuals on a care team.

00:44:25.902 --> 00:44:27.860
At Cityblock, we use
community health partners.

00:44:27.860 --> 00:44:30.250
These are folks who are
not clinically licensed.

00:44:30.250 --> 00:44:33.370
They're hired from the
communities that we serve.

00:44:33.370 --> 00:44:35.920
They are hired for empathy,
and for listening skills,

00:44:35.920 --> 00:44:37.300
and for trust building.

00:44:37.300 --> 00:44:39.310
And they go into
a patient's home

00:44:39.310 --> 00:44:41.632
and say, hey, it sounds
like that wound on your leg

00:44:41.632 --> 00:44:42.590
isn't looking so great.

00:44:42.590 --> 00:44:45.550
What if we just video the doctor
in right now to look at that?

00:44:45.550 --> 00:44:47.410
They're facilitating
that interaction

00:44:47.410 --> 00:44:50.150
that allows the doctor to be
more efficient with their time,

00:44:50.150 --> 00:44:52.210
but still has that
human contact.

00:44:52.210 --> 00:44:53.880
And using those
individuals in the trust

00:44:53.880 --> 00:44:56.005
that they build with our
patients and our community

00:44:56.005 --> 00:44:58.070
members as a bridge to
the health care system

00:44:58.070 --> 00:45:00.137
is also incredibly powerful.

00:45:00.137 --> 00:45:02.720
So I agree, I think technology
has to be part of the solution,

00:45:02.720 --> 00:45:05.560
but it does not
function particularly

00:45:05.560 --> 00:45:07.900
in this population with
absent, really solid

00:45:07.900 --> 00:45:11.285
trusted human relationships.

